esident and vice president. The\nibate was scarcely under way when\nliournment was taken.\nFLOCK TO FARM.\npwards of Ten Thousand Persona\nVisit Scene of Crimea.\nUporte, Ind\u201e May 12.\u2014All roads In\n\u25a0ports county led to the Guinness\nra Sunday, upwards of 15,000 sight\ntrs visiting the place of death he\nle the sun set Practically every\nWebdodled resident of this city made\nftrip, and the railroads and trolley\nas brought about 4.000 more to the\nV Mayor Darrow found It necea\n0 to issue stringent orders that\nj* Sunday closing laws should \u00bbe\nItaly be enforced and the hotels and\n\u2022torants were overrun with pat\nJ Practically every conveyance\nF-the town was pressed Into service\nan attempt to provide fransporta\nfor the crowdB In the afternoon.\nkw proved insufficient, and the late\n\u00abers were forced to make their way\nthe place on foot.\nvestlgatlou of the case by the au\nlies halted, the sheriffs and oth\nwho went to the farm being\nWWed to become mere spectators\nr several of the out of town vls\np, however, were seeking Informa\n\"coocerulng missing friends or rel\nd some further Information\nI,\u201e .posslbl* Identity of the\n>Ictima of the farm resulted\nleb inquiries.\nB06t definite Information came\nLlndbee. 610 LaSalle street.\nHe said that his brother.\n0r^ f\u00b0r Mrs. Guinness\nhwLag?\u2019 and that the\n.be iad from him contaln\n\u2122a l\u00b0n 'hat Thomas intended\nhis employer. Olaf wrote to\nhat tu lttl<' latpr- an<l she re\n0I,, 0IaaH Llndbee had gone\n\u25a0om M8nd tbat sbe had bad no\nden, \u00b0laf IJ\u201cdb\u00bb* viewed\n\u201ctitled corpses, but was un\ne dd aay.l\u2018kenp88 to his broth\nled bundles of bones and\n,Mrt Herron Released.\n!Use, N v\niadv Ma>' 12.\u2014Mrs. Her-,\nOf be^n MSt0d \u00b0n a traln SU8\u2018\naurder(\u00bbfqNIrS' Gu,nnp8s. the In- j\nPereas, was released.\nBanf\u00b0Rd SUICIDES.\nA[Wy 0fficer Ends His Exist-!\ntagton* ^8h,nflt0n\ni Ma^ 12\u2014Charles E.\nmduate of West Point.\nHeut 8Ue<1 frODl tke array as\nid kiineadnth!\u201c s\u00aePtetnber. 1906.\nRegent w i11?6\" ,n h*8 room\n,lv^nt hotel In this city. Hts\n1 recent! T.ron,on- N. J Ban-1\nring wl(1f bf^n engaged in civil\na letter *a,!r0a<1 at E1 Pa80>\n\u201coral a addrpS8\u00abd Adju\ntoTrth- \u201ckln\u00ab 'or\nbis pocktrt! a,rmJ' Wh,ch was\n1 his vi\u201eu ,eada 10 tbe be\nPurpot(. 'Vashlngton was\n1. of being restored to\n|PL,ED Buchanan.\nAS* Pr<,vent^ Mem\n\u00abSou!rQett,n\u00ae H,t\nGrn baseball league\ngame at Memphis Sunday the loea\nteam did not secure a hit off Pitcher\nBuchanan of the Uttie Rock club.\nThe score was 1 to 0 in favor of the\nvisitors.\nBaseball Players Arrested.\nMobile. May 12 Every member of\nthe New Orleans and Mobile teams\nand the two umpires were arrested be\nfore the first ball was pitched o\nSunday\u2019s game, the charge being play\ning Sunday baseball. Bond was Im\nmediately given in th\u00ab sum of UOO\nEXfODES UNDER STAIRS.\nAttempt Is Made to Blow Up a\nCouple of Families.\nChicago, May 12.\u2014What appears to\nhave Men an attempt to assassinate\nVlnyenz.o Vlvlrlto and Pietro Mosotto\nand their families at No. 31 Gault\nCourt was mude early Monday.\nA dynamite bomb was exploded un\nder the stairway leading to the apart\nments of both families. The attempt\nto kill the families, the police assert,\nwas made to prevent them from ap\npearing as witnesses against Antonio\nMarlcl and his son, Vito, who are to he\ntried In the criminal court on a charge\nof conspiracy to commit murder.\nJoseph Concillo, who was shot and\nkilled Feb. 2 by Battlste Scardini, had\nlived at the houBe which friends of\nthe latter and Marici, so the police\nsuppose, attempted to blow up.\nScardini and Marcl when, according\nto the police, their letters containing\nthreats, failed to intimidate the victim\nenough to cause him to leave $500 in\na certain spot for them, decided to\nkill him and, it Is alleged the former\nmiieu me iiauan ana es\ncaped.\nVivlrlto and Mosotto live on the\nfirst and second floors of the two\nstory brick building, respectively, and\nwere preparing to retire when the\nbomb was exploded. It tore away a\nlarge part of the rear wall of the\nstructure and wrecked the stairway.\nNone of the persons in the house\nwere hurt, but all were thrown into\na panic No one was seen in the vi\ncinity of the house.\nPECULIAR SITUATION.\nBrought About By an Opinion of the\nCourt of Appeals.\nAustin. May 12.\u2014A peculiar situa\ntion has developed regarding the\nopinion of the court of civil appeals\nin the double daily train service over\nthe Victoria division of the Galveston.\nHarrisburg and San Antonio railway\nThe court decided In favor of the state\non points of law Involved In litigation,\nand at the same time the railroad com\npany by perpetuating Its Injunction\nagainst the enforcement of the rail\nroad commission order. The state\ncannot nppeal the case, as the law\nwas decided In Its favor, and the rail\nroad will not appeal, as It won on se\ncuring its Injunction. The railroad\nwould like to appeal, but cannot, and\nthe state has no grounds for an appeal\nSeveral officials of the Rock Island\nrailroad headed by J. W. Robbins,\nvice-president and general manager\nare here protesting against the val\nuation placed on eleven miles of com\npleted road of the Rock Island from\nIrring to Carrollton. Dallas county,\nby the railroad commission. Officials\nclaim the valuation is too low and\nwant the commission to raise it.\nBequest Left College.\nAustin. May 12.\u2014The educational\ndepartment has received a comnmnloa\nIrm f rnm Qf imhun vllln rnnrnvln cr flut\nInformation that Captain T. Wilkinson,\na well known citizen, had died and left\n$6,000 to John Tarleton college This\namount Is set aside In his will and\nwill be allowed to go to the college.\nIt will be used by the college authori\nties to build a girls' dormitory.\nCOMMITTEE CALLS.\nPresident Urged to Favor Plan For\nReturn of Prosperity.\nWashington, May 12.\u2014A committee\nfrom tho National Prosperity associa\ntion of St. Ixuiis, called on President\nRoosevelt to urge his aid In furthering\nplans for encouraging the return of\nprosperity throughout the country\nThe committee found the president\ncordial in his treatment and frank in\nexpressions of willingness to aid them\nIn every way possible. A short speech\nwas made by E. C. Simmons, chairman\nof the executlVe committee of the as\nsoclatlon which was responded to by\nthe president.\nDERRINGER BESIDE BODY.\nJames A. Padgett Receives Bullet In\nHeart From Old Weapon.\nDallas, May 12.\u2014With an old fash\nioned Derringer pfstol beside his body,\nJames A. Padgett was found lyUig cold\nIn death In a room at his residence In\nthis city Monday mhrnlng. The corpse\nwas on the bed and a bullet had pene\ntrated the heart. Deceased, who was\nsixty-nine years old, leaves a widow\nand three sons.\nValuable Papers Stolen.\nFort Worth. May 12\u2014Officers of\nNational Livestock Commission com\npany of North FOrt Worth found the\nbig safe open and rifled. The robbery\nwas committed by experts or some one\nfamiliar with the offlcee. as the com\nbtnatlon was used. There was no\nmoney In the vault, but a number of\nvaluable papers were stolen.\ni\nTWO HUNDRED DIE.\nAwful Epidemic Prevailing In\nRussian Prison.\n'Kiev. Russia. May 12.\u2014A frightful\nepidemic of exanthematenus typhoid\nlu raging In the city prison. More than\n100 deaths so far have occurred, and\npractically all of the inmates are In\nfected. The authorities are withhold\ning details.\nCROP DISPOSED OF.\nWesley Love Has Sold Mis Bermuda\nOnions In Laredo Section\nJacksonville, Tex., May 12.\u2014Wesley\nLove, one of the most extensive peach\ngrowers in the south, has Just closed\nout his onion crop wrown in the La\nredo country. Mr. Love had fifty\nacres In Bermuda onions, from which\nhe shipped fifty-four cars. Tie had\nA. 1\u201e Brooks of this place in the\nnorthern markets looking after their\ndisposition. Mr. Brooks has Just re\nturned and reports satisfactory prices.\nBesides Mr. Ix>ve, there are other\nJacksonville citizens interested in\ngrowing onions in the Laredo country,\namong them being Ambrose Johnson\nand Alexander Bros. All have made\na succcess of the vegetable and truck\nIndustry in this part of the state, and\nseveral years ago made considerable\ninvestments in southwest Texas which,\nit la stated, have proven quite profit\nable.\nHARD-HITTING HARLAN.\nDespite Hie Advanced Age Justice\nWields Well the Willow.\nWashington. May 12.\u2014Associate Jus\ntice Harlan, despite his seventy-five\nyears, took part In a baseball game\nSaturday. He got three hits, keeping\nthe outfield busy chasing his long\ndrives.\nTwo teams, one coached by Justice\nPeele of the court of claims .contend\ned for supremacy. Justice Harlan's\nteam won. An hour before the game\nthe Justice, with shirt sleeves rolled\nup and the typical expression of one\nstrictly on to the job, started to bat\nthem out in practice, and he kept the\nqounger parties racing all over the\nfield.\nJustice Harlan also triumphed In\nthe rifle shoot, scoring nine bullseyes\nout of a possible twelve.\nBaby Has Narrow Escape.\nParis, Tex., May 12.\u2014The fifteen\nmonth-old daughter of W. J. Kelso got\nhold of some purgative pellets con\ntaining one-sixtieth of a grain of\nstrychnine each and ate several of\nthem. Soon afterward sha began to\nhave convulsions. A doctor was In\nstantly summoned and the baby was\npronounced out of danger.\nNOTICE.\nis hereby given that the school\nboard of Prescott will recciv*\nsealed bids for the erection of\na two-fttory brick school build\ning; plans and specifications o.\nwhich can be seen nt Hamby\nHaynio\u2019s office in Prescott. Ark.\nor, at the offices of (5ibb Sr>n\nders, architects, nt Little Ho k.\nArkansas.\nThe bids to be opene 1 June 1\n1DOH, and contract awarded to\nlowest responsible lv ider. iVur\nto be given for completion of the\nwork and the board reserves